\end{array}\right],\ldots
\end{gathered}
\]

\end_inset

at which point we reach another milestone.
 The oven temperature does not jump another 
\begin_inset Formula $21^{\circ}$
\end_inset

F at this point.
 It will only increase another 
\begin_inset Formula $5^{\circ}$
\end_inset

F, so is essentially up to working temperature.
 The first 
\begin_inset Formula $14.5$
\end_inset

 minutes of baking brings the oven to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim350^{\circ}$
\end_inset

F and the brownies to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim103^{\circ}$
\end_inset

F, a state that the brownies baking in a preheated oven reached in about
 
\begin_inset Formula $2.5$
\end_inset

 minutes.
 To summarize, brownies in a cold oven took 
\begin_inset Formula $14.5$
\end_inset

 minutes to get to the same point (oven temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $350^{\circ}$
\end_inset

F, brownie temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $103^{\circ}$
\end_inset

F) the brownies reached in a preheated oven in only 
\begin_inset Formula $2.5$
\end_inset

 minutes.
 From here out it is safe to assume the baking will proceed similarly.
 Therefore it takes 12 more minutes to bake brownies starting in a cold
 oven than it does starting in a preheated oven.
 We simply add 12 minutes to the baking time and proceed.
 Presumably this applies to any baking done at 
\begin_inset Formula $350^{\circ}$
\end_inset

F.
 The first 14.5 minutes of baking starting with a cold oven are equivalent
 to only 
\begin_inset Formula $2.5$
\end_inset

 minutes of baking starting with a preheated oven.
