\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
first order homogeneous discrete dynamical system
\series default
 is an equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{x}_{k+1} & =\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}_{k}),\label{eq:dds-recurrence}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which paired with an 
\series bold
initial condition
\series default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{v}\label{eq:dds-initial-condition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

defines a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{0},\mathbf{x}_{1},\mathbf{x}_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dds-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is an example of a 
\series bold
recurrence
\series default
 or 
\series bold
recurrence relation
\series default
 and determines all of the terms of the sequence except the first, which
 must be supplied separately.
 For purpose of our study of linear algebra, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{k}$
\end_inset

 are in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model-part1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can be rewritten in terms of this definition by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{k}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
M(k)\\
T(k)
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

, from which it follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}_{k}) & =\left[\begin{array}{c}
M(k)\\
T(k)
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
21\\
\frac{1}{146}(M(k)-T(k))
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{c}
M(k)\\
T(k)
\end{array}\right]+\frac{1}{146}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
M(k)\\
T(k)
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
21\\
0
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
M(k)\\
T(k)
\end{array}\right]+\frac{1}{146}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
M(k)\\
T(k)
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
21\\
0
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\left(\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right]+\frac{1}{146}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right]\right)\left[\begin{array}{c}
M(k)\\
T(k)
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
21\\
0
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\frac{1}{146}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
146 & 0\\
1 & 145
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
M(k)\\
T(k)
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
21\\
0
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\frac{1}{146}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
146 & 0\\
1 & 145
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x}_{k}+\left[\begin{array}{c}
21\\
0
\end{array}\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is an example of a 
\series bold
nonlinear discrete dynamical system
\series default
 as the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

 is not linear.
 More precisely in this case, the system is 
\series bold
affine
\series default
.
 It takes the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{x}_{k+1}=M\mathbf{x}_{k}+\mathbf{b}.\label{eq:affine-dynamical-system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted in the definition, a discrete dynamical system determines a sequence.
 Our first order of business is to understand how so.
 For each initial condition, the sequence defined by a discrete dynamical
 system can be calculated term-by-term.
 The recurrence relation defines each term after the first.
 For example, the first few terms of the sequence defined by the system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{x}_{k+1} & =\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
-.15 & -1.3 & -1.95\\
-.55 & 1.8 & 3.15\\
.15 & -1.3 & -2.25
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x}_{k}+\left[\begin{array}{c}
2\\
-5\\
4
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:recurrence-example1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

with initial condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}_{0}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
8\\
-5\\
6
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

can be calculated as follows.
 According to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:recurrence-example1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{x}_{1}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
-.15 & -1.3 & -1.95\\
-.55 & 1.8 & 3.15\\
.15 & -1.3 & -2.25
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x}_{0}+\left[\begin{array}{c}
2\\
-5\\
4
\end{array}\right] & =\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
-.15 & -1.3 & -1.95\\
-.55 & 1.8 & 3.15\\
.15 & -1.3 & -2.25
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
8\\
-5\\
6
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
2\\
-5\\
4
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
-4.4\\
.5\\
-1.8
\end{array}\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Also according to (
