\series default
 of a square matrix is the maximum of the magnitudes (absolute values) of
 its eigenvalues.
 The magnitude of a complex number 
\begin_inset Formula $a+ib$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\frac{\sqrt{6}+\sqrt{2}}{4}\pm i\frac{\sqrt{6}-\sqrt{2}}{4}\right| & =\sqrt{\left(\frac{\sqrt{6}+\sqrt{2}}{4}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{\sqrt{6}-\sqrt{2}}{4}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\sqrt{\frac{6+2\sqrt{12}+2}{16}+\frac{6-2\sqrt{12}+2}{16}}\\
 & =\sqrt{\frac{6+2+6+2}{16}}\\
 & =1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Much like a geometric series, which converges when the ratio is less than
 one and diverges when the ratio is greater than one, an affine system will
 approach the fixed point when the spectral radius is less than one and
 will generally tend toward infinity when the spectral radius is greater
 than one.
 The analogy ends there.
 An affine dynamical system whose matrix has spectral radius one can exhibit
 several different behaviors: tendency toward infinity and periodicity as
 seen above, but also convergence to a fixed point, depending on the system
 and the initial condition.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{digression}{Long Term Behavior}
\end_layout

\end_inset

For an affine discrete dynamical system, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{k+1}=M\mathbf{x}_{k}+\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, where 1 is not an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the system has a unique fixed point:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M\mathbf{x}^{*}+\mathbf{b} & =\mathbf{x}^{*}\\
M\mathbf{x}^{*}-\mathbf{x}^{*} & =-\mathbf{b}\\
(M-I)\mathbf{x}^{*} & =-\mathbf{b}\\
\mathbf{x}^{*} & =-(M-I)^{-1}\mathbf{b}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $M-I$
\end_inset

 exists because 1 is not an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}=\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{x}^{*}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{y}+\mathbf{x}^{*}$
\end_inset

, and substituting into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{k+1}=M\mathbf{x}_{k}+\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y}_{k+1}+\mathbf{x}^{*} & =M(\mathbf{y}_{k}+\mathbf{x}^{*})+\mathbf{b}\\
 & =M\mathbf{y}_{k}+\left(M\mathbf{x}^{*}+\mathbf{b}\right)\\
 & =M\mathbf{y}_{k}+\mathbf{x}^{*}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}_{k+1}=M\mathbf{y}_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The analysis of this linear dynamical system fully informs the behavior
 of the affine system.
 Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is diagonalizable, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}_{0}=\mathbf{x}_{0}-\mathbf{x}^{*}$
\end_inset

 (by substitution) and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}_{0}$
\end_inset

 in terms of a basis of eigenvectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{w}_{1},\mathbf{w}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{w}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2},\ldots,\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{y}_{0}=c_{1}\mathbf{w}_{1}+c_{2}\mathbf{w}_{2}+\cdots+c_{n}\mathbf{w}_{n}
\]

\end_inset

for some scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2},\ldots,c_{n}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}_{1}=M\left(c_{1}\mathbf{w}_{1}+c_{2}\mathbf{w}_{2}+\cdots+c_{n}\mathbf{w}_{n}\right)=c_{1}\lambda_{1}\mathbf{w}_{1}+c_{2}\lambda_{2}\mathbf{w}_{2}+\cdots+c_{n}\lambda_{n}\mathbf{w}_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}_{2}=M\left(c_{1}\lambda_{1}\mathbf{w}_{1}+c_{2}\lambda_{2}\mathbf{w}_{2}+\cdots+c_{n}\lambda_{n}\mathbf{w}_{n}\right)=c_{1}\lambda_{1}^{2}\mathbf{w}_{1}+c_{2}\lambda_{2}^{2}\mathbf{w}_{2}+\cdots+c_{n}\lambda_{n}^{2}\mathbf{w}_{n}$
\end_inset

, and so on:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{y}_{k}=c_{1}\lambda_{1}^{k}\mathbf{w}_{1}+c_{2}\lambda_{2}^{k}\mathbf{w}_{2}+\cdots+c_{n}\lambda_{n}^{k}\mathbf{w}_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

This solution is dominated by the eigenvalue(s) with the greatest magnitude.
 If the dominant magnitude is less than one, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}_{k}$
\end_inset

 will tend toward zero and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{k}$
\end_inset

 will tend toward the fixed point.
 If the dominant magnitude is greater than one, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}_{k}$
\end_inset

 will tend toward infinity as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}\neq0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|\lambda_{j}|>1$
\end_inset

, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{k}$
\end_inset

 will tend toward infinity.
